@database SIMConfig.guide
@width 77

@node Main "SIMConfig Documentation"
@next "Page_0"
@prev "Main"
@toc "Main"


  This is the online help manual for SIMConfig.  It basically contains all
information and hints needed to configure SIM correctly.  Further information
can be found in the documentation of SIM.



		@{" General Information             " Link Page_0}

		@{" CPU and Memory Configuration    " Link Page_1}
		@{" User Environement Configuration " Link Page_2}
		@{" Debugger Window Control         " Link Page_3}
		@{" Function Keys                   " Link Page_4}
		@{" Enabled Warnings                " Link Page_5}
		@{" Miscellaneous Settings          " Link Page_6}


@endnode

@node Page_0 "General Information"
@next Page_1
@prev Main
@toc "Main"

  When started, SIMConfig opens a window on the Workbench screen.  The menu
contains the following items:



    About         Displays the program version, the version of SIM and to    
    ~~~~~         who it is registered to. 


    Help          Activates the online help for the current configuration
    ~~~~          Page.  Requirements therefore are that the AmigaGuide
                  library is available and that this document is in the
                  same directory as SIMConfig.


    Load	  Loads a configuration.
    ~~~~

    Save As	  Saves a configuration.
    ~~~~~~~

    Generate      Saves a configured copy of SIM.
    ~~~~~~~~

    Test	  Loads a copy of SIM with the current configuration into
    ~~~~	  memory and invokes it.
    
    Quit          Quits SIMConfig.
    ~~~~



  At the bottom of the window are always the following gadgets:



    Next Page     Switches to the next configuration page.
    ~~~~~~~~~

    Prev Page     Switches to the previous configuration page.
    ~~~~~~~~~

    Generate      Opens a filerequester and requests a path to save SIM.
    ~~~~~~~~ 

    Quit          Quits SIMConfig.
    ~~~~


  When you generate a configured copy of SIM, use 'sim2' as file name and
preferably 'c:' as directory.  Otherwise most tools will not find SIM when
they need to load it.



@endnode


@node Page_1 "CPU and Memory Configuration"
@next Page_2
@prev Page_0
@toc "Main"

  On this page you can set the CPU, FPU and MMU and memory configuration of
the Amiga on which SIM will be used.

  To set the CPU, FPU and MMU configuration use the following gadgets. When
SIMConfig is started, these will be set to the current configuration, except
that 68EC020 processors are not distinguished from 68020.  Please note that
if SIM is not correctly configured it will not work:



    CPU           Selects the CPU. You can choose between 68000, 68010,
    ~~~           68020, 68EC020, 68030, 68EC030, 68040, 68EC040 and 68LC040.


    FPU           Selects the FPU. Depending on the setting of the CPU switch,
    ~~~           you can choose between none, 68881/2, 68040 and 68040+EMU
                  (68040 with FPSP).


    MMU           Selects the MMU. Depending on the setting of the CPU switch,
    ~~~           you can choose between none, 68851, 68030 and 68040.


    Leave MMU on  Specifies wether or not SIM will leave the MMU on while
    while active  SIM is active.  Unless you intend to play around with the
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~  MMU tree while SIM is active, leave this gadget checked.


    Address bus   Selects 24 or 32 bit bus width for memory management. This
    ~~~~~~~~~~~   gadget will automatically change to the right setting when
                  the CPU is set.  If 24 bit bus width is selected, the
                  leading 8 bits of addresses are ignored.



  To specify the start- and end addresses and type of all memory blocks use 
the next gadgets.  You will only be able to view and edit memory which is
declared.  When SIMConfig is started, all memory for which a memory list
exists will be automatically detected, including the Kickstart image. If you
add or modify pages, they will be checked for correctness.



    Add new       Adds a new page.  The number of pages is limited to 6.
    ~~~~~~~       Set the start- and end address and type in the 'Start',
                  'End' and 'Type' gadgets and press either 'Okay' to accept
                  or 'Cancel' to abort.


    Delete        Deletes a previously selected page in the list.  You are
    ~~~~~~        not allowed to remove the first entry of the list.


    Default       Restores the default memory configuration for this Amiga.
    ~~~~~~~   

    Start         Contains the start address of a previously selected or new
    ~~~~~         page.


    End           Contains the end address of a previously selected or new
    ~~~           page.


    Type          Specifies the type of a previously selected or new page.
    ~~~~          Use 'Graphics' for DMA capable memory, that is Chip memory
                  and 'ROM' for read only memory. Otherwise use 'Normal'.


    Okay          Accepts changes done to a page.
    ~~~~ 

    Cancel        Ignores changes done to a page.
    ~~~~~~


@endnode

@node Page_2 "User Environement Configuration"
@next Page_3
@prev Page_1
@toc "Main"

  On this page you can set preferences concerning the environement of SIM:



    Text mode     Selects either insert or overwrite mode for text entry.
    ~~~~~~~~~

    Keymap        Selects the custom keymap of SIM.
    ~~~~~~

    Font          Selects the font graphics.  Currently available are both
    ~~~~          old and new 'Topaz80' and 'DarkParticle'.


    Mouse speed   Selects either slow or fast mouse speed.
    ~~~~~~~~~~~

    Resolution    Selects the display resolution of SIM.
    ~~~~~~~~~~

    Custom        Contains the name of the current custom display.
    ~~~~~~

    Select        Opens a file requester and loads a monitor configuration
    ~~~~~~        for the custom resolution.  The loaded display definition
                  will only be used when 'Resolution' is on 'Custom'.


    Display       Specifies the number of bytes a loader shall allocate for
    allocation    display or backup of the display.  If you choose this value
    ~~~~~~~~~~    20480 bytes larger than needed for the default display size,
                  DD disk activites can be handled in background.  For HD disk
                  operations, 40960 bytes oversize are required.


    Color FG      Selects foreground color. The color is encoded as $RGB.
    ~~~~~~~~

    BG            Selects background color. The color is encoded as $RGB.
    ~~



@endnode

@node Page_3 "Debugger Window Control"
@next Page_4
@prev Page_2
@toc "Main"

  On this page you can set preferences concerning the debugger window:



    Window active Selects wether or not the window is displayed by default.
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Large	  Selects if the register list in the window is either small
    register list (3 lines) or large (10 lines)
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Second	  Selects the second register list.  This can be either CPU
    register list (advanced CPU registers like VBR, CACR etc.), MMU or FPU.
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Buttons	  Selects if the right part of the footer shall contain
    displayed	  a set of buttons or status information.
    ~~~~~~~~~

    Display	  Selects which views will be displayed.
    ~~~~~~~

    Mode	  Selects the mode of the respective view.  Note that for
    ~~~~	  'Source' and 'History' only one view is alowed.

    Size	  Specifies the size of the respective view in lines.
    ~~~~

    Link to	  Specifies the expression to which the term is linked to.
    ~~~~~~~	  A term that begins with a '=' will absolutely set the
		  view start to the result of the expression, where as for
		  expressions beginning with a '>', the view start is only
                  set if the result of the expression is not within the
		  current memory clip that is displayed.

@endnode

@node Page_4 "Function Keys"
@next Page_5
@prev Page_3
@toc "Main"

  On this page you can edit the definitions of the function keys:



    F1-F10        Contain the current definition for the respective function
    ~~~~~~        key, concidering the setting of 'Qualifier'.  If the string
                  is a command line which will be directly executed when the
                  key is pressed, it ends with an '@'.


    Qualifier     Specifies the qualifier.  Currently only 'NONE' and 'SHIFT'
    ~~~~~~~~~     are used.


    Clear         Clears all function key definitions.
    ~~~~~    



@endnode

@node Page_5 "Enabled Warnings"
@next Page_6
@prev Page_4
@toc "Main"

  SIM displays warnings for various reasons.  On this page you can select
the warnings you would like to see and turn off the ones you don't want
to know about.

  Please refere to the documentation of SIM for more information about
warnings.

@endnode

@node Page_6 "Miscellaneous Settings"
@next Page_1
@prev Page_5
@toc "Main"

  On this page you can edit varoius settings:



    Character set Selects wether only printable characters shall be displayed
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~ or all characters shall be printed.


    Replace with  Specifies the replacement character for unprintable
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~  characters.


    Tabulator     The number of columns of a TAB for text and source
    size          display.
    ~~~~~~~~~

    History       Selects either the internal buffer or the work memory
    storage       for storage of history entries.
    ~~~~~~~


    External size Specifies how much of the work memory shall be used for
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~ history storage.


    Store         Specifies wether all registers shall be stored or only
    registers     CPU registers.
    ~~~~~~~~~



@endnode

